XVII.

Who lets his children wander at their whim,

Choosing their road, as though not bound by him: But all their life is rounded with a shade,

And every road goes down behind the rim!

XVIII.

And there behind the rim, the swift, the lame, At different paces, but their end the same,

Into the dark shall one by one go down, Where the great furnace shakes its hair of fiame.
